---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import StorySection from '../components/StorySection.astro';
import ChartEmbed from '../components/ChartEmbed.astro';
import FakeChart from '../components/FakeChart.astro';
---

<Layout>
  <div class="story-container">
    <!-- Hero -->
    <header style="text-align: center; margin-bottom: 4rem;">
      <h1>Rising Tides,<br />Shrinking Worlds</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">How a warming ocean cascades into hunger, thirst, and loss across the Pacific</p>
      <p style="font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--muted);">A story for the Pacific Dataviz Challenge 2026</p>
    </header>

    <!-- Intro -->
    <StorySection>
      <p>
        The Pacific Ocean is not just water—it is home, highway, and lifeline for millions. 
        But as the planet warms, this vast blue expanse is turning into a threat multiplier, 
        setting off a chain reaction that touches every aspect of life on the islands.
      </p>
    </StorySection>

    <!-- Beat 1: Ocean on Fire -->
    <StorySection title="1. An Ocean on Fire">
      <p>
        Sea surface temperatures across the Pacific have been climbing for decades. 
        This extra heat isn't just an abstract number—it fuels stronger storms, 
        bleaches corals, and disrupts the marine food web that millions depend on.
      </p>
    </StorySection>

    <!-- Fake line chart for temperature anomaly -->
    <FakeChart type="line">
      <span slot="caption">Mean sea surface temperature anomaly (placeholder data)</span>
    </FakeChart>

    <!-- Later you'll replace with a real Plotly embed: 
    <ChartEmbed src="temp-anomaly.html" height={500}>
      <span slot="caption">Mean sea surface temperature anomaly (°C), 1950-2025. Source: Pacific Data Hub</span>
    </ChartEmbed>
    -->

    <!-- Beat 2: Sea Level Rise -->
    <StorySection title="2. The Water Is Rising">
      <p>
        Warmer water expands, and melting ice adds volume. For low-lying atolls, 
        a few centimetres of rise means the difference between a safe home and a flooded one.
        In some places, the sea is creeping inland faster than anyone predicted.
      </p>
    </StorySection>

    <FakeChart type="bar">
      <span slot="caption">Sea level anomalies for selected Pacific nations (mm, placeholder)</span>
    </FakeChart>

    <!-- Beat 3: Disasters & Displacement -->
    <StorySection title="3. When the Sea Attacks">
      <p>
        Higher seas make storm surges deadlier. Cyclones, once manageable, now leave
        a trail of destruction. The number of people directly affected by disasters
        has spiked, along with economic losses that small island economies can ill afford.
      </p>
    </StorySection>

    <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 2rem;">
      <FakeChart type="bar">
        <span slot="caption">Affected persons (thousands)</span>
      </FakeChart>
      <FakeChart type="bar">
        <span slot="caption">Economic loss (USD millions)</span>
      </FakeChart>
    </div>

    <!-- Beat 4: Thirst -->
    <StorySection title="4. No Water to Drink">
      <p>
        As the sea pushes underground, freshwater lenses—fragile layers of drinking water
        beneath atolls—turn salty. Progress toward safely managed drinking water is stalling
        or reversing in the most exposed communities.
      </p>
    </StorySection>

    <FakeChart type="bar">
      <span slot="caption">% of population with safely managed drinking water (placeholder)</span>
    </FakeChart>

    <!-- Beat 5: Fragile Economies, Glimmers of Hope -->
    <StorySection title="5. A Delicate Balance">
      <p>
        Tourism, often the backbone of these economies, is vulnerable to the very impacts
        that keep visitors away: coral bleaching, beach erosion, and disaster headlines.
        Yet across the region, renewable energy is quietly growing, offering a glimpse of a
        more resilient future.
      </p>
    </StorySection>

    <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 2rem;">
      <FakeChart type="line">
        <span slot="caption">Tourist arrivals (thousands)</span>
      </FakeChart>
      <FakeChart type="bar">
        <span slot="caption">Renewable energy share (%)</span>
      </FakeChart>
    </div>

    <!-- Closing -->
    <StorySection>
      <p style="text-align: center; margin-top: 3rem; font-weight: 600; font-size: 1.1rem;">
        The data shows a region on the frontline—but also one fighting back.
        Every decimal point of temperature matters. Every adaptation effort counts.
        The Pacific's story is ours to understand and to act on.
      </p>
      <p style="text-align: center; color: var(--muted); margin-top: 2rem;">
        Built for the Pacific Dataviz Challenge 2026 · Data from <a href="https://pacificdata.org" target="_blank">Pacific Data Hub</a>
      </p>
    </StorySection>
  </div>
</Layout>